    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>120600</citedRange></bibl>. 
                Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#cdl-maffre2018"/></bibl>, whence 
                <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/> <citedRange>68.1746</citedRange></bibl></p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><w lemma="δεκάτα">Δεκά<supplied reason="lost">τα</supplied></w> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Dîme <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Tithe <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Decima <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>In contrast with all the other inscriptions on the rim of basins (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr108900</ref> to <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr120500</ref>),
                which were cut skillfully in workshops, this one looks rather like a graffito. The mention of the tithe might either have been added when the offering was 
                already placed in the sanctuary or be the result of a later appropriation.</p>
	       <p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
